      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="vol-2-P_M-d2e355-person" n="vol-2-P_M-Abraham-1">
               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">אברהם<ref corresp="#d2e343"/>
               </persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Abraham</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gr"><ref corresp="#d8e4"/>
               </persName>
               <persName xml:lang="checkme"/>
               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Christian monk<ref corresp="#d2e367"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>–</note>
               </state>
               <bibl>Antiochus Monachus,PG89, 1692</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>Proselyte<ref corresp="#d2e387"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>6th-7thC<ref corresp="#d2e400"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e360" n="1"> On this form see vol. 3, Abraham (13) B/M,
                            p. 72. </note>
               <note xml:id="d2e367" n="2"> The story of
                            this person’s conversion to Judaism begins with the words: <span xml:lang="checkme">   </span>
                            (there was a certain exemplary monk). If this is the name he adopted
                            after he converted, this is the first instance of the name Abraham
                            serving for converts. Later on it became the standard name for male
                            proselytes, see Introduction 1.1.1.1.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e387" n="3"> See previous
                            note and vol. 1, Introduction 6.3.3, p.
                    50.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e400" n="4">
                            See H. Sivan, Palestine in Late Antiquity (Oxford
                            2008) 51.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
